theorem.p:
	  Let f=(u,v):\Bbb R^2\to\Bbb R^2 and let \Omega\subset\Bbb R^2 be a domain.
	  Then the following are equivalent:



f is holomorphic in \Omega;

f is continuously differentiable at every point of \Omega;

(Cauchy-Riemann equations) u and v, as real maps, have continuous partial derivatives
	    and satisfy 
	    \begin{cases}u_x&\!=v_y\cr u_y&\!=-v_x\cr\end{cases}
	    at every point of \Omega;


f is continuously differentiable at every point of \Omega as a real map and f_{\bar z}=0;

f is continuously differentiable at every point of \Omega and f(z)dz is a closed differential 1-form on \Omega;

(Cauchy integral formula) for all z\in\Omega there is a \rho_z such that
	    \displaystyle f(z) = \frac{1}{2\pi i}\!\!\int\limits_{C_z(r)}\frac{f(\zeta)}{\zeta-z}d\zeta
	    for any r\lt\rho_z. In particular, f is C^\infty;

f is analytic in \Omega, namely it can be written as a power series in some neighborhood of every z_0\in\Omega.
	    In other words, f is C^\omega;

f\in C^0(\Omega,\Bbb R^2) and it has a local holomorphic antiderivative around every point of \Omega;

(Cauchy's Theorem) f\in C^0(\Omega,\Bbb R^2) and \displaystyle\int\limits_\gamma f(z)dz=0 for every
	    piecewise-C^1 contractible loop \gamma inside \Omega;

(Runge's Theorem) on any compact K\subset\Omega, f is the uniform limit
	    of a sequence of rational functions with a pole in each component of \overline{\Bbb C}\setminus K.
